WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.650 --> 00:00:02.090
ANGELA PRIMAVERA:
Hi, everyone.

00:00:02.090 --> 00:00:04.600
I'm Angela Primavera, curriculum
specialist here at

00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:06.410
the Google Children's Center.

00:00:06.410 --> 00:00:09.880
And when I was thinking about
a phrase that could describe

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:13.530
our next guest, what kept coming
to mind was the power

00:00:13.530 --> 00:00:15.110
of connection.

00:00:15.110 --> 00:00:18.192
For anyone who's been to a
Michael Franti show, you know

00:00:18.192 --> 00:00:20.980
that he has a way of reaching
out to each and every member

00:00:20.980 --> 00:00:22.940
of the audience.

00:00:22.940 --> 00:00:26.230
For over 20 years, Michael has
found a way to connect not

00:00:26.230 --> 00:00:30.960
only with his musical fans, but
people around the globe.

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:34.660
Whether it's bridging a
conversation using just his

00:00:34.660 --> 00:00:39.270
guitar, as documented in his
film "I Know I'm Not Alone,"

00:00:39.270 --> 00:00:44.710
or utilizing technology to
connect to his fans in FranTV,

00:00:44.710 --> 00:00:47.320
or even his Power to the
Peaceful festivals right here

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:51.200
in the Bay Area, Michael Franti
embraces the power of

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:52.780
connection.

00:00:52.780 --> 00:00:56.020
More recently, he's used his
poetic abilities to connect

00:00:56.020 --> 00:00:59.610
with our newest generation of
environmental stewards in his

00:00:59.610 --> 00:01:04.000
children's book "Where in the
World Is Away?" In partnership

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.320
with Talks at Google, Google
Play, and the Google

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:10.410
Children's Center's Parent
Education Series, I'm honored

00:01:10.410 --> 00:01:13.280
to offer Googlers this
opportunity to connect once

00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:15.521
again with Michael Franti.

00:01:15.521 --> 00:01:23.868
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:23.868 --> 00:01:25.950
MICHAEL FRANTI: How's
it going, y'all?

00:01:25.950 --> 00:01:28.626
How you feeling?

00:01:28.626 --> 00:01:30.940
All right.

00:01:30.940 --> 00:01:36.750
Well, I was really excited to
come to Google today because,

00:01:36.750 --> 00:01:42.070
well, there's this urban myth
about Google, which is--

00:01:42.070 --> 00:01:42.740
that I--

00:01:42.740 --> 00:01:44.530
can you push that
in for me, Jay?

00:01:44.530 --> 00:01:49.140
That I believed up until about
15 minutes ago, which is that

00:01:49.140 --> 00:01:52.790
when you type in something on
Google, there's this giant

00:01:52.790 --> 00:01:58.270
room full of 1,000 people
in lab coats.

00:01:58.270 --> 00:02:03.350
And they see what you've typed
in, like Roberto Clemente's

00:02:03.350 --> 00:02:05.600
batting average in 1967.

00:02:05.600 --> 00:02:10.009
And then a guy gets up, and he
runs down this corridor to

00:02:10.009 --> 00:02:13.050
this shelf full of books
and encyclopedias.

00:02:13.050 --> 00:02:14.940
And he pulls it out, and
he thumbs through it.

00:02:14.940 --> 00:02:17.230
