born in April?

00:07:51.955 --> 00:07:53.610
The earth.

00:07:53.610 --> 00:07:55.670
The earth was-- you
can Google it.

00:07:55.670 --> 00:07:59.290
Earth was born in April.

00:07:59.290 --> 00:08:02.670
And this is a book that's about

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:04.840
taking care of our Earth.

00:08:04.840 --> 00:08:09.130
And it's called, "Where in the
World is Away?" And it goes a

00:08:09.130 --> 00:08:10.880
little something like this.

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:14.060
Little Lee and little
Lou sat by a lake,

00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:16.170
sharing a bottle of juice.

00:08:16.170 --> 00:08:19.830
It was a warm, sunny day, and
the birds where at play.

00:08:19.830 --> 00:08:23.690
And they smiled as they
watched mama goose.

00:08:23.690 --> 00:08:26.620
As they finished the drink, Lou
pulled back his arm and

00:08:26.620 --> 00:08:29.560
said, I'm going to
throw it away.

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:30.300
Stop, Lou.

00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:33.440
Think, before you make
a mistake, where in

00:08:33.440 --> 00:08:36.460
the world is away?

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:39.690
If we throw it in the lake,
it's gone for today.

00:08:39.690 --> 00:08:42.580
But is that really away?

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:46.185
Not for the frogs who hip hop
on the logs or the fish who

00:08:46.185 --> 00:08:49.540
jump up in the air or the little
tiny things that live

00:08:49.540 --> 00:08:52.715
off the greens that grow on
the bottom down there.

00:08:55.540 --> 00:08:58.990
All of our spills just fill up
their gills, and it's so hard

00:08:58.990 --> 00:09:00.850
to breathe without air.

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:02.510
They play hide and
go seek, and they

00:09:02.510 --> 00:09:05.280
think, school is cool.

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:07.950
So we shouldn't make
a mess down there.

00:09:07.950 --> 00:09:10.530
I've got a plan, Lou
started to say.

00:09:10.530 --> 00:09:13.700
Over the hill's where
I'll throw it away.

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:17.120
Not so fast, Lou,
if I may say.

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:20.130
Is over the hill there
really away?

00:09:20.130 --> 00:09:20.970
What do you kids think?

00:09:20.970 --> 00:09:21.980
Is that really away?

00:09:21.980 --> 00:09:22.720
AUDIENCE: No.

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:24.310
MICHAEL FRANTI: No.

00:09:24.310 --> 00:09:26.560
That's where the forest
grows, tall and wide.

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:29.630
And all kinds of critters
live deep inside.

00:09:29.630 --> 00:09:32.560
It's cool in the daytime
and warm at night.

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:36.980
And squirrels do twirls while
birds are in flight.

00:09:36.980 --> 00:09:38.600
There's nuts, and
there's berries.

00:09:38.600 --> 00:09:40.770
There's bears, and there's
fairies and a

00:09:40.770 --> 00:09:43.030
butterfly up in a tree.

00:09:43.030 --> 00:09:46.740
By the light of the moon, they
play drums with raccoons as

00:09:46.740 --> 00:09:51.140
the mice shout, one,
two, three.

00:09:51.140 --> 00:09:54.400
Can I hear you kids say, one,
two, three, like mice?

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:56.240
AUDIENCE: One, two, three.

00:09:56.240 --> 00:09:56.660
MICHAEL FRANTI: Yay!

00:09:56.660 --> 00:10:00.420
[LAUGHS]

00:10:00.420 --> 00:10:04.170
But if the forest has bottles
on a hot, sunny day, the sun

00:10:04.170 --> 00:10:07.970
magnifies and might set it
ablaze, then all of the forest

00:10:07.970 --> 00:10:10.310
beings would run
with a fright.

00:10:10.310 --> 00:10:12.210
We don't want that, Lou.

00:10:12.210 --> 00:10:14.450
No, you're right.

00:10:14.450 --> 00:10:17.100
Lou said, let's just throw
it here on the street.

00:10:17.100 --> 00:10:20.190
Someone will come and
eventually sweep.

00:10:20.190 --> 00:10:23.580
But look down below, even
up through the cracks.

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:27.290
There grows the tiniest
blades of green grass.

00:10:27.290 --> 00:10:31.040
And where there is grass,
then grasshoppers be.

00:10:31.040 --> 00:10:33.260
And where there are
grasshoppers,

00:10:33.260 --> 00:10:35.380
let's let them be.

00:10:35.380 --> 00:10:38.050
And besides, we all like to
keep the street neat.

00:10:38.050 --> 00:10:42.780
And we don't need glass where
there might be bare feet.

00:10:42.780 --> 00:10:44.590
There's far too much garbage.

00:10:44.590 --> 00:10:46.150
It's just got to stop.

00:10:46.150 --> 00:10:51.220
The landfills are filling
right up to the top.

00:10:51.220 --> 00:10:54.890
Then where is away, said
confused little Lou.

00:10:54.890 --> 00:10:58.250
And what of the bottle when
there's no more juice?

00:10:58.250 --> 00:11:02.860
They spotted a bin with a round
symbol on it, and can

00:11:02.860 --> 00:11:05.660
with the word recycling on it.

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:09.580
And inside the can there were
hundreds of bottles in all

00:11:09.580 --> 00:11:13.790
kinds of shapes and
colors and models.

00:11:13.790 --> 00:11:17.620
If we put it in there, will it
go away, sweet little Lou

00:11:17.620 --> 00:11:19.290
started to say.

00:11:19.290 --> 00:11:22.510
Lee opened her mouth to
say, we'll never know.

00:11:22.510 --> 00:11:27.300
And just as she did,
along came a crow.

00:11:27.300 --> 00:11:32.200
This grow at her feet was oh,
so unique, a crow named Mo

00:11:32.200 --> 00:11:35.860
with a beak that could speak.

00:11:35.860 --> 00:11:37.130
Good heavens, they shouted.

00:11:37.130 --> 00:11:38.520
How could this be?

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:40.350
The crow said, relax.

00:11:40.350 --> 00:11:42.270
It's just a little old me.

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:45.060
If you'd like to know where old
bottle should go, close

00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:51.470
your eyes, spread your wings,
and follow this crow.

00:11:51.470 --> 00:11:55.020
The bottles are picked up by
truck and transported to a

00:11:55.020 --> 00:11:59.480
glass sorting center, then
they are sorted.

00:11:59.480 --> 00:12:02.620
Green ones go there, and
brown ones go here.

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:07.620
There's places for blue and
for yellow and clear.

00:12:07.620 --> 00:12:10.140
All of the paper and
caps are removed.

00:12:10.140 --> 00:12:14.430
And yes, even those things
are recycled too.

00:12:14.430 --> 00:12:18.430
All of the glass gets crushed
into cullet, a word you

00:12:18.430 --> 00:12:20.870
mightn't heard, but that's
what they call it.

00:12:26.790 --> 00:12:29.910
Then it's thrown into a
furnace to heat to a

00:12:29.910 --> 00:12:33.110
temperature of over
2000 degrees.

00:12:33.110 --> 00:12:36.020
And then when it's melted,
it glows into goo.

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:41.810
And then there are so many
things you can do.

00:12:41.810 --> 00:12:45.560
You can bend it and shape it and
pour it into molds, make

00:12:45.560 --> 00:12:48.480
magical art work or
things to be sold.

00:12:48.480 --> 00:12:51.880
And when it cools down, it
turns hard very fast and

00:12:51.880 --> 00:12:55.880
quickly returns int shiny,
smooth glass.

00:12:55.880 --> 00:12:59.190
It makes mirrors and lamps and
grape jelly jars, even

00:12:59.190 --> 00:13:01.740
eyeglasses and windows
for cars.

00:13:01.740 --> 00:13:04.120
There's so many things,
so many to choose.

00:13:04.120 --> 00:13:09.450
And yes, you can even make
bottles for juice.

00:13:09.450 --> 00:13:12.550
So always recycle, said
crow with a smile.

00:13:12.550 --> 00:13:15.710
And reduce what you use
every once in a while.

00:13:15.710 --> 00:13:20.120
When you reach for that bottle
high up on the shelf, remember

00:13:20.120 --> 00:13:25.300
away is just somewhere else.

00:13:25.300 --> 00:13:27.930
There's so many choices,
said sweet little Lou.

00:13:27.930 --> 00:13:32.180
But this here bottle, we're
going to reuse.

00:13:32.180 --> 00:13:34.740
And they each put
a flower in it.

