00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:48.690
other things?

00:18:48.690 --> 00:18:50.590
That's awesome.

00:18:50.590 --> 00:18:52.020
Awesome.

00:18:52.020 --> 00:18:52.720
Cool.

00:18:52.720 --> 00:18:53.810
All right.

00:18:53.810 --> 00:18:56.300
Well, we were going to just open
it up to any questions

00:18:56.300 --> 00:18:58.790
for any Googlers, perhaps
if you have for

00:18:58.790 --> 00:18:59.820
us, about any subject.

00:18:59.820 --> 00:19:03.110
It doesn't have to be about
worms and poop.

00:19:03.110 --> 00:19:06.770
But it can also be about
that, if you want.

00:19:06.770 --> 00:19:08.060
ANGELA PRIMAVERA: I'll go
ahead and start it off.

00:19:08.060 --> 00:19:08.930
MICHAEL FRANTI: OK, go ahead.

00:19:08.930 --> 00:19:10.635
ANGELA PRIMAVERA: And for those
of you on the VC, you

00:19:10.635 --> 00:19:13.430
can add it to the Dory
at goto slash Franti.

00:19:13.430 --> 00:19:17.730
Or anybody here can go ahead
and step up to the mic.

00:19:17.730 --> 00:19:21.340
So you found an inspirational
way to use your voice to

00:19:21.340 --> 00:19:22.850
connect with those around you.

00:19:22.850 --> 00:19:25.765
Is there a message that you
have for some of our young

00:19:25.765 --> 00:19:28.400
children here about the
power of their voice?

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:32.130
MICHAEL FRANTI: Well, my message
to every kid here is

00:19:32.130 --> 00:19:34.940
that all of us are different.

00:19:34.940 --> 00:19:38.680
And being different
is beautiful.

00:19:38.680 --> 00:19:43.450
When you look in your house at
something that's like a salad,

00:19:43.450 --> 00:19:48.370
if you have tomatoes in there
and carrots and greens and

00:19:48.370 --> 00:19:49.550
sprouts and--

00:19:49.550 --> 00:19:52.400
what are kinds of things you
guys put in your salads?

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:53.860
What do you put in your
salad at home?

00:19:56.500 --> 00:19:57.490
Avocado?

00:19:57.490 --> 00:19:58.740
I love avocado.

00:20:01.680 --> 00:20:02.090
Tea?

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:02.650
JAY BOWMAN: Cheese.

00:20:02.650 --> 00:20:03.290
MICHAEL FRANTI: Cheese.

00:20:03.290 --> 00:20:03.610
Oh, yeah.

00:20:03.610 --> 00:20:06.710
We love cheese.

00:20:06.710 --> 00:20:08.760
What?

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:09.270
Fruits.

00:20:09.270 --> 00:20:09.390
Yeah.

00:20:09.390 --> 00:20:10.320
Yeah, fruits.

00:20:10.320 --> 00:20:13.660
So the more things that are in
the salad, the more beautiful

00:20:13.660 --> 00:20:15.640
and tasty the salad is.

00:20:15.640 --> 00:20:17.490
And that's the same thing with
people in our world.

00:20:17.490 --> 00:20:21.950
The more difference that we have
and the more diversity--

00:20:21.950 --> 00:20:25.420
we call it-- that we respect
and love and honor and

00:20:25.420 --> 00:20:28.100
cherish, the better
the world is.

00:20:28.100 --> 00:20:31.410
So that's my message to kids,
same as to adults.

00:20:31.410 --> 00:20:35.260
Be your authentic self.

00:20:35.260 --> 00:20:36.510
Live your truth.

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:43.190
AUDIENCE: Pizza.

00:20:43.190 --> 00:20:43.340
MICHAEL FRANTI: Pizza.

00:20:43.340 --> 00:20:45.780
You put pizza in your salad?

00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:47.030
You do?

00:20:50.332 --> 00:20:51.582
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:00.610 --> 00:21:01.370
AUDIENCE: What'd you say?

00:21:01.370 --> 00:21:03.191
I didn't hear.

00:21:03.191 --> 00:21:04.441
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:06.960 --> 00:21:08.165
MICHAEL FRANTI: Nice, nice.

00:21:08.165 --> 00:21:10.230
You put salad in the garbage
when it's done.

00:21:14.180 --> 00:21:15.190
ANGELA PRIMAVERA: I'll go ahead
and ask another one.

00:21:15.190 --> 00:21:15.630
MICHAEL FRANTI: OK, cool.

00:21:15.630 --> 00:21:17.240
ANGELA PRIMAVERA: Feel free to
hop up on the mic there.

00:21:17.240 --> 00:21:19.400
We also have books for those of
you that would like to ask

00:21:19.400 --> 00:21:22.240
a question of Michael.

00:21:22.240 --> 00:21:24.010
What is something you've learned
from fatherhood that

00:21:24.010 --> 00:21:26.650
you'd like to share with us?

00:21:26.650 --> 00:21:28.280
MICHAEL FRANTI: That I'm
wrong most of the time.

00:21:33.250 --> 00:21:35.360
Being a dad, you have to make
it up as you go along.

00:21:35.360 --> 00:21:39.530
I have one son who's 25 and
another son who's 14.

00:21:39.530 --> 00:21:42.240
And I was really young when
I had my first son.

00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:51.870
And so when you have a kid, your
first kid, your time--

00:21:51.870 --> 00:21:54.810
you have to do all the wonderful
things in life that

00:21:54.810 --> 00:21:58.945
you do, like go to parties and
hang out at the beach and do

00:21:58.945 --> 00:21:59.900
all these things.

00:21:59.900 --> 00:22:02.050
It gets eliminated.

00:22:02.050 --> 00:22:04.760
And so you have the time
with your kids.

00:22:04.760 --> 00:22:08.350
And then you have like just
that one hour or two hours

00:22:08.350 --> 00:22:11.200
that you have for yourself
every day.

00:22:11.200 --> 00:22:15.560
And so what I did during that
time is I would take care of

00:22:15.560 --> 00:22:19.190
my son all day and then
put him to sleep.

00:22:19.190 --> 00:22:24.260
And he would go off with his mom
after that in the night.

00:22:24.260 --> 00:22:27.820
And I'd go to work at night at
nightclubs in San Francisco.

00:22:27.820 --> 00:22:29.860
But I'd have one or
two hours at home.

00:22:29.860 --> 00:22:31.010
And I would just write.

00:22:31.010 --> 00:22:34.270
I had these yellow legal pads
of paper that I would

00:22:34.270 --> 00:22:35.850
write lyrics on.

00:22:35.850 --> 00:22:39.400
And at first, I was like,
man, my time is gone.

00:22:39.400 --> 00:22:41.160
But then it really makes
you think about

00:22:41.160 --> 00:22:43.910
what you want to do.

00:22:43.910 --> 00:22:45.560
What's the most important
thing that you want to

00:22:45.560 --> 00:22:46.680
do with your time?

00:22:46.680 --> 00:22:48.190
And for me, it was writing.

00:22:48.190 --> 00:22:54.230
And so it really helped me to
hone in on what I love and

00:22:54.230 --> 00:22:59.590
what my passion is and to really
do my best during those

00:22:59.590 --> 00:23:01.080
moments that I had.

00:23:01.080 --> 00:23:04.970
And my mom was--

00:23:04.970 --> 00:23:07.140
she is an amazing woman.

00:23:07.140 --> 00:23:09.380
Mrs. Franti adopted me.

00:23:09.380 --> 00:23:12.230
And she had three kids
of her own with my

00:23:12.230 --> 00:23:13.640
father, Charles Franti.

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:15.530
And they're Finnish Americans.

00:23:15.530 --> 00:23:18.570
And they adopted myself and
another African American son.

00:23:18.570 --> 00:23:23.240
So we grew up in this house,
a diverse household.

00:23:23.240 --> 00:23:25.150
I have one sister
who's lesbian.

00:23:25.150 --> 00:23:28.440
And it's a very mixed
household.

00:23:28.440 --> 00:23:34.060
And one time I asked my mom.

00:23:34.060 --> 00:23:38.470
I said, what did you
do with us kids?

00:23:38.470 --> 00:23:41.160
You worked as a school
teacher for 35 years.

00:23:41.160 --> 00:23:42.770
Then you'd come home and
deal with us five kids.

00:23:42.770 --> 00:23:45.890
And she said, every
day I'd come home.

00:23:45.890 --> 00:23:50.240
And I had one expectation of all
of you, which is that when

00:23:50.240 --> 00:23:52.430
you went out into our
neighborhood, you treated

00:23:52.430 --> 00:23:55.040
everybody as good or better
than you wanted to

00:23:55.040 --> 00:23:57.440
be treated at home.

00:23:57.440 --> 00:24:02.100
And she said, I tried to teach
all of you kids and treat all

00:24:02.100 --> 00:24:06.930
of you kids exactly the same,
which meant that if one of us

00:24:06.930 --> 00:24:10.210
got a lollipop, then all
of us had to share it.

00:24:13.170 --> 00:24:14.220
I'm just kidding.

00:24:14.220 --> 00:24:17.630
I don't advise that
to any parent.

00:24:17.630 --> 00:24:20.150
But she insisted that we
treat every kid in our

00:24:20.150 --> 00:24:21.720
neighborhood the same.

00:24:21.720 --> 00:24:25.560
And she said that the greatest
gift that any parent could

00:24:25.560 --> 00:24:29.320
give their children is wings.

00:24:29.320 --> 00:24:33.530
And the wings are the self
confidence you have, that when

00:24:33.530 --> 00:24:36.390
you're in whatever precipice
in your life, that you feel

00:24:36.390 --> 00:24:41.280
like I have the ability to
jump off and fly and face

00:24:41.280 --> 00:24:44.380
whatever it is that this
challenge is in my life.

00:24:44.380 --> 00:24:48.550
And so that's what I try to
do with both my sons.

00:24:48.550 --> 00:24:51.970
And my mom did a really
great job with that,

00:24:51.970 --> 00:24:54.850
I think, with me.

00:24:54.850 --> 00:24:55.090
ANGELA PRIMAVERA: All right.

00:24:55.090 --> 00:24:56.770
We have a question from
the audience.

00:24:56.770 --> 00:24:57.270
MICHAEL FRANTI: Cool.

00:24:57.270 --> 00:24:57.770
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:24:57.770 --> 00:24:58.630
Thank you for coming out.

00:24:58.630 --> 00:24:59.470
And we really appreciate it.

00:24:59.470 --> 00:24:59.820
MICHAEL FRANTI: You're
welcome.

00:24:59.820 --> 00:25:01.760
AUDIENCE: What's the story
behind you being barefoot?

00:25:01.760 --> 00:25:04.480
And how often do you run into
a place where you think, no,

00:25:04.480 --> 00:25:05.920
probably not going
to go there?

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:10.510
MICHAEL FRANTI: Well, man,
walking onto the Google

00:25:10.510 --> 00:25:13.990
campus, I was like, ew, with a
name like Google, I don't know

00:25:13.990 --> 00:25:15.550
if I even want to--

00:25:15.550 --> 00:25:16.180
no.

00:25:16.180 --> 00:25:17.270
I've been barefoot--

00:25:17.270 --> 00:25:20.390
it'll be 13 years on my
birthday, which is at the end

00:25:20.390 --> 00:25:21.410
of this month.

00:25:21.410 --> 00:25:27.290
And I started walking barefoot
in countries where kids

00:25:27.290 --> 00:25:28.960
couldn't afford to wear shoes.

00:25:28.960 --> 00:25:31.140
And I'd go out and I'd play
soccer with them and stuff.

00:25:31.140 --> 00:25:35.480
And so I would take off my shoes
just to not stomp on

00:25:35.480 --> 00:25:36.970
their feet or whatever.

00:25:36.970 --> 00:25:39.150
And I could barely
take three steps.

00:25:39.150 --> 00:25:40.890
I was like, ouch, ouch, ouch.

00:25:40.890 --> 00:25:42.210
So I decided to go home.

00:25:42.210 --> 00:25:45.040
And for three days, I was
going to go barefoot.

00:25:45.040 --> 00:25:47.556
You have a question?

00:25:47.556 --> 00:25:49.492
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:49.492 --> 00:25:53.364
When did you learn guitar?

00:25:53.364 --> 00:25:54.830
AUDIENCE: When did
you learn guitar?

00:25:54.830 --> 00:25:57.210
MICHAEL FRANTI: When
did I learn guitar?

00:25:57.210 --> 00:25:59.980
I learned guitar not
too long ago.

00:25:59.980 --> 00:26:01.600
I've only been playing
guitar about seven or

00:26:01.600 --> 00:26:03.450
eight years, actually.

00:26:03.450 --> 00:26:04.220
Yeah.

00:26:04.220 --> 00:26:06.080
I started really late.

00:26:06.080 --> 00:26:08.450
I'll tell you more about
that in a minute.

00:26:08.450 --> 00:26:12.620
But so I decided to go barefoot
for three days.

00:26:12.620 --> 00:26:15.090
And three days turned into
a week and into a

00:26:15.090 --> 00:26:16.740
month and into a year.

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:22.810
And my son's waving
at me back there.

00:26:22.810 --> 00:26:26.020
He's like, dad, your
feet are gross.

00:26:26.020 --> 00:26:31.150
And there are times when I feel
like, wow, it's really

00:26:31.150 --> 00:26:31.750
gross around here.

00:26:31.750 --> 00:26:34.380
But I'm just more observant
of where I step.

00:26:37.070 --> 00:26:40.200
It's funny that you have to wear
shoes when you go into

00:26:40.200 --> 00:26:42.280
the airport, and then you have
to take them off when you go

00:26:42.280 --> 00:26:43.010
through the security.

00:26:43.010 --> 00:26:44.670
And then you got to put
them back on again.

00:26:44.670 --> 00:26:45.910
Then when you get on
the plane, you can

00:26:45.910 --> 00:26:46.590
take them off again.

00:26:46.590 --> 00:26:49.630
So I always carry a pair of
flip-flops around that are for

00:26:49.630 --> 00:26:51.490
those kind of moments.

00:26:51.490 --> 00:26:55.820
And I never do it out of
any form of protest.

00:26:55.820 --> 00:26:58.030
If I'm somewhere, and they say,
please put your shoes on,

00:26:58.030 --> 00:27:00.720
I always put my flip-flops on.

00:27:00.720 --> 00:27:04.470
And that's kind of the story.

00:27:04.470 --> 00:27:06.680
And when it was the tenth
anniversary of me being

00:27:06.680 --> 00:27:08.640
barefoot, I partnered with
this organization called

00:27:08.640 --> 00:27:10.130
Soles4Souls.

00:27:10.130 --> 00:27:13.850
And we collect used shoes
for kids and families

00:27:13.850 --> 00:27:15.820
all around the world.

00:27:15.820 --> 00:27:18.230
It started after Hurricane
Katrina.

00:27:18.230 --> 00:27:21.570
A lot of people left their
homes without shoes.

00:27:21.570 --> 00:27:25.310
And so they started collecting
shoes for that.

00:27:25.310 --> 00:27:29.890
But now we're in Haiti, South
America, Africa, places in

00:27:29.890 --> 00:27:31.140
Asia, all over the world.

00:27:34.610 --> 00:27:37.080
Oh, so my guitar--

00:27:37.080 --> 00:27:41.390
I went on this trip to this
place called Cuba.

00:27:41.390 --> 00:27:45.150
And I was there with a group of
musicians from around the

00:27:45.150 --> 00:27:48.610
world who are collaborating
with Cuban artists.

00:27:48.610 --> 00:27:52.330
And we were there singing the
songs that we'd written

00:27:52.330 --> 00:27:54.800
together during a week.

00:27:54.800 --> 00:27:58.120
And so every night, this guitar
would get passed around

00:27:58.120 --> 00:27:58.960
this table.

00:27:58.960 --> 00:28:02.830
And everybody would sort of sing
these wonderful boleros

00:28:02.830 --> 00:28:06.300
off into the Cuban Havana
moonlit night with bottles of

00:28:06.300 --> 00:28:08.350
rum and cigars being
passed around.

00:28:08.350 --> 00:28:15.690
And probably should lay off the
cigars and rum till you

00:28:15.690 --> 00:28:19.240
get your first chords
down, at least.

00:28:19.240 --> 00:28:23.360
And so I decided, I'm never
going to be caught in this

00:28:23.360 --> 00:28:25.320
situation when I can't
play guitar.

00:28:25.320 --> 00:28:26.750
And so a year passed.

00:28:26.750 --> 00:28:28.910
And I was at this great
festival up in Oregon.

00:28:28.910 --> 00:28:31.160
And the same thing, the guitar
got passed to me.

00:28:31.160 --> 00:28:33.060
And all I could do was go--

00:28:33.060 --> 00:28:34.310
[MUSIC - THE SUGARHILL GANG,
"RAPPER'S DELIGHT"]

00:28:38.400 --> 00:28:41.170
MICHAEL FRANTI: So I decided,
golly, I'm going

00:28:41.170 --> 00:28:41.960
to learn the guitar.

00:28:41.960 --> 00:28:44.710
So finally, another
year passed.

00:28:44.710 --> 00:28:46.580
And I was in another
embarrassing situation.

00:28:46.580 --> 00:28:49.100
And I was up with a friend of
mine who's a farmer up in

00:28:49.100 --> 00:28:50.350
Humboldt County.

00:28:53.740 --> 00:28:57.060
And I decided this would be the
perfect place to sit on

00:28:57.060 --> 00:29:02.370
his porch for hours and learn
my first guitar chords.

00:29:02.370 --> 00:29:04.360
And I've been playing now about
seven, eight years.

00:29:04.360 --> 00:29:05.870
And I love it.

00:29:05.870 --> 00:29:07.120
Yeah.

00:29:09.340 --> 00:29:09.590
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:29:09.590 --> 00:29:10.940
Thanks again for coming here.

00:29:10.940 --> 00:29:14.750
It is just terrific to have
people like you come visit us.

00:29:14.750 --> 00:29:16.680
So you've had this
amazing career.

00:29:16.680 --> 00:29:19.830
Musically, you've done an
incredible range of things,

00:29:19.830 --> 00:29:23.270
and then outside of music, from
video stuff to writing

00:29:23.270 --> 00:29:25.440
children's books to just
social projects.

00:29:25.440 --> 00:29:26.930
What are you most proud of?

00:29:26.930 --> 00:29:29.770
And what do you think is going
to have the biggest legacy?

00:29:29.770 --> 00:29:32.930
MICHAEL FRANTI: Well,
it's the same thing,

00:29:32.930 --> 00:29:33.860
the two same things.

00:29:33.860 --> 00:29:35.020
I'm most proud of my kids.

00:29:35.020 --> 00:29:37.745
And hopefully, my kids have
the biggest legacy.

00:29:37.745 --> 00:29:38.000
Right?

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:39.250
High five, son.

00:29:42.520 --> 00:29:44.800
There's a lot of things that
I've done in music.

00:29:44.800 --> 00:29:49.010
And the most memorable things
are being in places where

00:29:49.010 --> 00:29:52.210
music is absent most of the
time and then going and

00:29:52.210 --> 00:29:55.820
bringing music there and seeing
the environment change

00:29:55.820 --> 00:29:56.795
immediately.

00:29:56.795 --> 00:30:00.670
AUDIENCE: You had such an
eclectic career from your

00:30:00.670 --> 00:30:04.060
activism, social justice,
your films, to music.

00:30:04.060 --> 00:30:06.920
What inspired you to jump
into children's

00:30:06.920 --> 00:30:07.970
books of all things?

00:30:07.970 --> 00:30:12.170
And then I think what you
previously just said might

00:30:12.170 --> 00:30:13.010
explain that already.

00:30:13.010 --> 00:30:13.290
But--

00:30:13.290 --> 00:30:14.040
MICHAEL FRANTI: Yeah.

00:30:14.040 --> 00:30:14.940
OK.

00:30:14.940 --> 00:30:22.640
Well, my favorite artists
have been--

00:30:22.640 --> 00:30:28.240
my favorite artists are Bob
Marley, Marvin Gaye, John

00:30:28.240 --> 00:30:29.800
Lennon, and Johnny Cash.

00:30:29.800 --> 00:30:33.310
And the reason is because they
both-- or all of them were

00:30:33.310 --> 00:30:36.970
able to write songs about how
much they wanted to see the

00:30:36.970 --> 00:30:40.080
world be a better place.

00:30:40.080 --> 00:30:43.870
And then they would also write
a song right next to it about

00:30:43.870 --> 00:30:46.950
how much they love
their girlfriend.

00:30:46.950 --> 00:30:51.630
And I've always felt like if
you can't do both, or if

00:30:51.630 --> 00:30:54.620
you're only settled on just
doing one of those things,

00:30:54.620 --> 00:30:59.500
then you're missing so much
of what it's about.

00:30:59.500 --> 00:31:02.610
And so that's why I do
the different things.

00:31:02.610 --> 00:31:07.380
That's why I go to Iraq and play
music on the street and

00:31:07.380 --> 00:31:11.240
make a film about that and then
write a children's book,

00:31:11.240 --> 00:31:13.860
like this book, the other book
that's here, "What I Be,"

00:31:13.860 --> 00:31:16.720
which is about being yourself.

00:31:16.720 --> 00:31:19.920
And really, the message
is the same thing.

00:31:19.920 --> 00:31:23.930
It's about reaching out to other
people and being the

00:31:23.930 --> 00:31:26.820
person that you are and then
being able to embrace other

00:31:26.820 --> 00:31:32.620
people for being the person
that they are.

00:31:32.620 --> 00:31:35.930
And my mom used to always tell
me, it's not enough--

00:31:35.930 --> 00:31:37.360
she hated the word tolerance.

00:31:37.360 --> 00:31:38.830
That was a buzz word.

00:31:38.830 --> 00:31:39.980
We need to have tolerance.

00:31:39.980 --> 00:31:42.060
And there's a Museum of
Tolerance, which is a

00:31:42.060 --> 00:31:43.350
fantastic place.

00:31:43.350 --> 00:31:46.540
But she never liked the
word tolerance,

00:31:46.540 --> 00:31:48.370
because it was always--

00:31:48.370 --> 00:31:53.300
you tolerate getting your teeth
grinded at the dentist.

00:31:53.300 --> 00:31:58.240
But she liked the words like
embrace and to honor and to

00:31:58.240 --> 00:32:01.790
respect and cherish because
she's always felt like we

00:32:01.790 --> 00:32:05.400
should be that towards other
people, towards other

00:32:05.400 --> 00:32:10.540
cultures, other walks of life,
that to really live life and

00:32:10.540 --> 00:32:14.210
to live a fullness for yourself
is to find the beauty

00:32:14.210 --> 00:32:17.200
in other things that are
different than you.

00:32:17.200 --> 00:32:17.700
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:32:17.700 --> 00:32:19.200
MICHAEL FRANTI: Yeah.

00:32:19.200 --> 00:32:20.700
ANGELA PRIMAVERA: Go ahead.

00:32:20.700 --> 00:32:22.600
AUDIENCE: Did you do
any Johnny Cash

00:32:22.600 --> 00:32:25.710
songs at San Quentin?

00:32:25.710 --> 00:32:29.575
"Folsom Prison," or
"Cocaine Blues?"

00:32:29.575 --> 00:32:30.240
MICHAEL FRANTI: It was funny.

00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:33.270
Before we-- we also played
in Folsom Prison.

00:32:33.270 --> 00:32:33.670
AUDIENCE: Oh, wow.

00:32:33.670 --> 00:32:34.930
MICHAEL FRANTI: And we were
the first artists playing

00:32:34.930 --> 00:32:37.960
there in 37 years since Johnny
Cash had done it.

00:32:37.960 --> 00:32:43.800
And when we went in, the warden
of the prison required

00:32:43.800 --> 00:32:46.530
that I send a list of the songs
that I was going to sing

00:32:46.530 --> 00:32:48.960
and all the lyrics.

00:32:48.960 --> 00:32:53.740
And he went through line item,
veto style, and said, you

00:32:53.740 --> 00:32:54.510
can't sing this line.

00:32:54.510 --> 00:32:55.550
You can't sing this line.

00:32:55.550 --> 00:32:56.660
And you can't sing this song.

00:32:56.660 --> 00:32:57.910
And you can't sing this song.

00:32:57.910 --> 00:33:02.450
And at first, I was like,
man, this is not cool.

00:33:02.450 --> 00:33:04.050
I'm not going to do this.

00:33:04.050 --> 00:33:09.270
I got a pride feather
sticking out of me.

00:33:09.270 --> 00:33:11.560
And then I thought, these
cats are locked

00:33:11.560 --> 00:33:13.010
down for a long time.

00:33:13.010 --> 00:33:17.930
And who am I to not sing or not
show up because the warden

00:33:17.930 --> 00:33:19.450
won't let me sing a song?

00:33:19.450 --> 00:33:22.823
This is not the protest
that I want to make.

00:33:22.823 --> 00:33:25.480
So the answer to your question,
no, we weren't

00:33:25.480 --> 00:33:25.950
allowed to.

00:33:25.950 --> 00:33:26.675
And no, I didn't

00:33:26.675 --> 00:33:27.810
AUDIENCE: Oh, wow.

00:33:27.810 --> 00:33:29.910
Just Sesame Street.

00:33:29.910 --> 00:33:32.100
MICHAEL FRANTI: Well, there's
plenty of other

00:33:32.100 --> 00:33:34.120
songs besides that.

00:33:34.120 --> 00:33:37.350
But that's what--

00:33:37.350 --> 00:33:42.480
one of the things that we come
across as musicians is where

00:33:42.480 --> 00:33:43.860
are our values?

00:33:43.860 --> 00:33:46.250
And what are the lines that
we choose to cross?

00:33:46.250 --> 00:33:48.760
Are we going to put a
song in this movie?

00:33:48.760 --> 00:33:50.570
And if we put a song in the
movie, are we going to put a

00:33:50.570 --> 00:33:52.770
song in the commercial that
goes along with the movie?

00:33:52.770 --> 00:33:56.560
And then if that commercial also
has a partnership with

00:33:56.560 --> 00:33:58.670
some brand, do we support
that brand?

00:33:58.670 --> 00:34:01.640
Do we allow the song
to be in there?

00:34:01.640 --> 00:34:05.080
And at the end of the day, I
always feel like I'm out there

00:34:05.080 --> 00:34:08.995
every day of my life on tour,
singing things and expressing

00:34:08.995 --> 00:34:11.830
the things I can in the best
way I can for whatever the

00:34:11.830 --> 00:34:13.310
situation is.

00:34:13.310 --> 00:34:17.239
But I'll talk to these kids
differently than I would kids

00:34:17.239 --> 00:34:20.659
in San Quentin.

00:34:20.659 --> 00:34:23.239
AUDIENCE: What I really want to
