your favorable books?

00:34:25.199 --> 00:34:26.480
Or do your kids have
any favorite?

00:34:26.480 --> 00:34:27.520
MICHAEL FRANTI: Oh, yeah.

00:34:27.520 --> 00:34:30.340
My favorite books were the
"Curious George" books.

00:34:30.340 --> 00:34:30.875
AUDIENCE: Oh, yeah.

00:34:30.875 --> 00:34:32.030
MICHAEL FRANTI: Yeah.

00:34:32.030 --> 00:34:36.830
And "Harold and the Purple
Crayon." And then all of the

00:34:36.830 --> 00:34:42.940
Roald Dahl books, and especially
"Willy Wonka and

00:34:42.940 --> 00:34:44.250
the Chocolate Facotory."

00:34:44.250 --> 00:34:45.440
AUDIENCE: What about music
when you were young?

00:34:45.440 --> 00:34:46.804
What was the first
stuff that you

00:34:46.804 --> 00:34:47.929
listened to and then after?

00:34:47.929 --> 00:34:49.889
MICHAEL FRANTI: The first stuff
that I listened to was

00:34:49.889 --> 00:34:52.360
music that was in my house that
my brothers and sisters

00:34:52.360 --> 00:34:53.040
were playing.

00:34:53.040 --> 00:34:59.440
So it was Al Green, Jim
Croce, Carole King.

00:34:59.440 --> 00:35:02.240
And then it was The Clash and

00:35:02.240 --> 00:35:05.290
Parliament-Funkadelic and The Police.

00:35:05.290 --> 00:35:08.250
And then it became Run-DMC.

00:35:08.250 --> 00:35:10.490
Somewhere in all of that was
the "Saturday Night Fever"

00:35:10.490 --> 00:35:14.600
soundtrack which didn't leave
the turntable for a long time.

00:35:14.600 --> 00:35:15.880
Earth, Wind &amp; Fire.

00:35:15.880 --> 00:35:19.610
And then once I went through
all that stuff, I went

00:35:19.610 --> 00:35:23.730
straight into hardcore punk rock
for many years and just

00:35:23.730 --> 00:35:29.000
listen exclusively to all the
great Bay Area bands, Dead

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:34.320
Kennedys and the Circle Jerks
and all the bands that were

00:35:34.320 --> 00:35:36.450
touring through here.

